1205–1250","1230–Male":"1230–Deceased","1181–Male":"1181–Deceased","1213–1296":"1213–1296","1165–1269":"1165–1269","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","Abt 1185":"about 1185","1205":"1205","1269":"1269","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"about 1211","um 1213":"about 1213","1165":"1165","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1181":"1181","Knockin, Shropshire, England":"Knockin in Oswestry, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strange","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): nickname for a newcomer to a district, from Middle English <i>strange</i> ‘foreign’ (Old French <i>estrange</i>, Latin <i>extraneus</i>, from <i>extra</i> ‘outside’).","Irish (Antrim): this name is also common in Ireland, where, in addition to its English etymology, it may represent an Anglicized form of any of several Irish names containing the element <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’, e.g.   Doyle  ,   Gallagher  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stranger","meanings":["English: nickname for a newcomer to an area, from Middle English <i>stra(u)nger(e)</i> ‘stranger, foreigner’ (Old French <i>estrangier</i>). Compare   Strange  ."]},{"name":"Doyle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sean, Kieran, Seamus, Aileen, Dermot, Liam, Niall, Brennan, Brigid, Conal, Conan, Donal.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhghaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was used as a byname for Scandinavians, in particular to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from fair-haired Norwegians. Compare   McDougall  ,   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"Lestrange","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Strange   1 with fused Old French definite article <i>le</i>.","Irish: in Ireland, adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> ‘son of <i>Cúchoigcriche</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the borderland’. <i>Lestrange</i> was adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> probably due to the presence of a prominent family of Lestrange, of similar meaning, who settled in the counties of Westmeath and Offaly in the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"La","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice La Strange was born about 1185, in Knockin in Oswestry, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Philip le Strange, was 21 and her mother, Joyce Corbet, was 21. She married Richard de Leighton about 1211. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1185–":"umbes 1185–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1205–1250":"1205–1250","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1181–Male":"1181–Surnud","1213–1296":"1213–1296","1165–1269":"1165–1269","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","Abt 1185":"umbes 1185","1205":"1205","1269":"1269","1213":"1213","Abt 1211":"umbes 1211","um 1213":"umbes 1213","1165":"1165",